 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">4</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">A photon sphere is a region of highly curved space-time around a black hole where gravity is so strong, light photons are forced to travel in closed orbits (not be confused with a black hole&apos;s smaller event horizon, passed which no light, particles or information escapes). This gives rise to a light &apos;halo&apos; around the black hole</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">5</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">Because the top of the vortex cross-section approximates to the size of the central concentration of bubbles, one possible drawback of this model is that it might suggest to students that a galaxy&apos;s supermassive black hole is as large as its central bright bulge of stars. This is obviously incorrect when comparing the radius of the Milky Way&apos;s central black hole—41 light seconds—with that of its central bright bulge of stars—a single light year [, 29: #pedaa62e9bib029]. It is envisaged that in a teaching situation, this apparent mismatch would be pointed out, and used to emphasise the awesome gravitational and evolutionary influence of supermassive black holes on their host galaxies. I thank a referee for pointing this out</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
